About
A long story that winds through the centuries: with its 2300 years of history, the Appia Antica shows intact the signs of an illustrious and fascinating past, still clearly visible among the ruins that overlook the roadside. Episodes of great history and daily life have echoed in this idyllic setting since the times of ancient Rome, in a continuous development between the "dark ages" of the Middle Ages, passing through the Renaissance, up to the creation of the open-air museum wanted by Pope Pius IX in the mid-nineteenth century. The Via Appia Antica began at Porta Capena, near the Circus Maximus, to continue southwards with a linear and easy route until it reached Capua and then Brindisi.
Duration: More than 3 hours

    A great find, Appian Way. A getaway from the crowds of Rome
    A great find. We did a self guided, own pace walk along the Appian Way. About a 40 minute walk from Roma, Termini, to one end of the walk. The information centre is quite good and provided us with a couple of maps, one that had information for a self guided tour. (The other was €2). The path has some gentle hills but is generally flat for the most part. Many stops along the way, including catacombes, ancient mausoleums, C4 BC building and mosaics. There are also a couple of cafes and bars to stop in at. We took the bus back to the Metro after about 8km. There is a lot more to explore if you feel up to it. Great history. On a Sunday you will only come across people and bikes NO cars allowed. Highly recommend.
    Visited October 2023

    Appian Way is an ancient Roman raod
    My trip from Brindisi to Rome took place along the Appian Way; Brindisi has been connected by the Adriatic Sea to this southern Roman highway since 312 BC. The Appian Way is a key connection of Brindisi to Rome that has endured for thousands of years. The Appian Way is one of the ancient world's historic and longest connections. It is likely to be created as a UNESCO World Heritage List that connects Rome with the south of Italy, which has existed for thousands of years. Among local destinations are Pompeii and Naples, which are related to the Appian Way.

Great fun taking a bike ride on the original super Highway
May 2024 • Solo
I have been to Rome for a week several years ago, but had a couple day layover en route to Egypt recently, and on the suggestion of a relative rented an e-bike for a couple of hours and went a few miles down the Appian way.

It’s hard to believe you’re just within a few miles of the city center. The neighborhood has a very rustic, almost village, like feel to it. I actually saw a shepherd. Also, a herd of goats just wondering along the Appian Way and grazing as they went. Lots of old monuments to , citizens of ancient in more recent Rome that your way. Great fun, but if you’re taking a bike, you need to wear a helmet and be paying attention to where your tire is about to go as the pavement is very uneven it would be extremely easy to have a wheel get caught between two stones, and take a tumble

I had a great lunch at the restaurant next to the place. I rented the E bike.

I am Magine during the summer peak season. It’s a pretty much a mob scene most days so you should go very early or maybe late afternoon if you’re traveling there on the weekends or during the busy summer season. I would strongly recommend doing a weekday visit regardless of what time of year you’re there.
